  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="10" relname="preparation">1) Leading Indicators (April)</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="8" relname="span">
2) Steep declines in capital spending commitments and building permits, along with a drop in
the money stock pushed the leading composite down for the ftfth time in the past 11 months to
a level 0.5% below its high in May 1984.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="7" relname="span">
3) Such a decline is highly unusual at this stage in an expansion;</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="3" relname="evidence">
4) for example, in the three most recent expansions, the leaders were rising, on average, at
about a 7% clip at comparable phases in the cycle.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="6" relname="concession">
5) While not signaling an outright recession,</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="9" relname="span">
6) the current protracted sluggishness of the leading indicators appears consistent with our
prognosis of sluggish real GNP growth over the next few quarters.</segment>
<group id="7" type="span" parent="2" relname="elaboration" />
<group id="8" type="span" parent="10" relname="span" />
<group id="9" type="span" parent="8" relname="interpretation" />
<group id="10" type="span" parent="11" relname="span" />
